T1  - The Colour of the Unborn: Anti-Abortion and Anti-Bussing Politics in Michigan, United States, 1967-1973
AN  - 1660023515; 201508717
AB  - In October 1972, anti-abortion activists campaigned in Michigan to prevent the liberalisation of the state's 126-year-old abortion laws. Going door-to-door, they distributed over one million brochures warning voters against the consequences of supporting abortion reform in the November election. They blanketed football games, shopping malls and university campuses with anti-abortion flyers in the hope of swaying voters. The flyers were colour-coded: anti-abortion forces mailed red brochures to doubtful voters and mailed blue brochures to every identifiable African American voter in Michigan. The blue brochures contained images of black children, whereas the red brochures did not. This colour coding reflected and reinforced the racial geography of Michigan and concretely shaped the cultural imagining of the foetus. Michael Deeb, a leader of the anti-abortion forces, explained that, 'The entire focus of the campaign was to change the image from a fetus to one of an unborn child and thus . . . the votes to our side'. The transformation of the image of the foetus into an image of a child was intentionally achieved through racial frameworks, themselves reflective of pre-existing racial conflicts such as school integration and welfare. Michigan's statewide referendum on abortion in November 1972, just two months shy of the Supreme Court's Roe v. Wade decision, which effectively permitted women to have abortions during the first trimester, illuminates how emerging discourses of sexuality and race helped mobilise support for conservative politics in the United States during the 1970s. Against the backdrop of George Wallace's Democratic primary victory, the Nixon and McGovern presidential campaigns and the battles over bussing students to racially integrated schools, Michigan voters debated whether to reform the state's abortion laws. The 1972 referendum on abortion acted as an 'agenda-setting tool' that transformed a national political environment by providing an instrument through which conservatives and liberals engaged in social movement mobilisation, advertising, media coverage and coalition building around sexual, gender and racial conflicts. Because of its economic importance, its abundance of Catholic and blue-collar voters and its status as a bellwether for northern urban race relations, Michigan mattered profoundly in the political calculus of both major parties. Adapted from the source document.
